{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1780128169861,"sessionID":"ses_18818249cffeInllmWUcVkPFl1","part":{"id":"prt_e77e83f84001qUl1TPtMxaAdhS","messageID":"msg_e77e8390f001cmfTlwe5oWz4bn","sessionID":"ses_18818249cffeInllmWUcVkPFl1","snapshot":"3bb07697e0b2084573cf2765d81da51c20a297d1","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780128174585,"sessionID":"ses_18818249cffeInllmWUcVkPFl1","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_function_uq6cuwlcg0ve_1","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/spec.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/spec.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: \"Feature Specification: deep-improvement — skill-benchmark mode + rename\"\n3: description: \"Phase parent: rename deep-agent-improvement to deep-improvement and add Lane C (skill-benchmark) measuring a skill's real-world routing, unprompted reference/asset discovery, efficiency, and usefulness; multi-model deep research (001) informs rename (002), Lane C build (003), and validation/docs (004).\"\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode\"\n6:   - \"skill-benchmark mode\"\n7:   - \"deep-improvement skill rename\"\n8: importance_tier: \"important\"\n9: contextType: \"implementation\"\n10: _memory:\n11:   continuity:\n12:     packet_pointer: \"skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode\"\n13:     last_updated_at: \"2026-05-30T00:00:00Z\"\n14:     last_updated_by: \"claude-opus\"\n15:     recent_action: \"Authored parent spec + 4-phase structure\"\n16:     next_safe_action: \"Run multi-model deep research in 001-skill-benchmark-deep-research\"\n17:     blockers: []\n18:     completion_pct: 10\n19:     open_questions: []\n20:     answered_questions: []\n21: ---\n22: <!-- SPECKIT_TEMPLATE_SOURCE: spec-core | v2.2 -->\n23: <!-- SPECKIT_LEVEL: 3 -->\n24: <!-- CONTENT DISCIPLINE: PHASE PARENT — root purpose + sub-phase control + what needs done; no migration narrative (see context-index.md); heavy docs live in children. -->\n25: \n26: # Spec 122 — deep-improvement: skill-benchmark mode + skill rename\n27: \n28: **Track:** skilled-agent-orchestration\n29: **Type:** Phase parent (sub-phase control file)\n30: **Status:** In progress — Phase 001 (deep research) active\n31: **Level:** 3 (architecture-affecting; multi-phase)\n32: \n33: ---\n34: \n35: ## 1. Purpose\n36: \n37: Evolve the `deep-agent-improvement` skill into a broader **`deep-improvement`** evaluation skill and add a third evaluation lane that benchmarks *skills themselves*.\n38: \n39: Two coupled changes:\n40: \n41: 1. **Rename `deep-agent-improvement` → `deep-improvement`.** The skill no longer only improves agent `.md` files. It already carries Lane A (agent-improvement) and Lane B (model-benchmark), and this packet adds Lane C (skill-benchmark). The `-agent-` infix in the name is now too narrow and miscommunicates scope.\n42: \n43: 2. **Add Lane C — skill-benchmark mode.** A new evaluation lane that measures whether a *skill* is actually well-structured, well-routed, efficient, and useful **in practice** — i.e. how real AI agents discover and use it in situ — and emits actionable findings that a follow-up packet can remediate.\n44: \n45: This is the phase-parent control file. Heavy per-phase docs (`plan.md`, `tasks.md`, `checklist.md`, `implementation-summary.md`, `decision-record.md`) live in the sub-phases where the work happens. Migration notes for the placeholder→real phase restructure live in `context-index.md`, not here.\n46: \n47: ---\n48: \n49: ## 2. Background / current state\n50: \n51: `deep-agent-improvement` (evaluator-first bounded improvement) currently ships:\n52: \n53: - **Lane A — agent-improvement** (`/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop`): proposal-first loop over a bounded agent `.md`, dynamic-mode 5-dimension scoring, guarded promotion/rollback.\n54: - **Lane B — model-benchmark** (`/deep:start-model-benchmark-loop`): benchmark a model or prompt framework against repeatable fixtures; pattern or 5-dim scoring; deterministic or graded runs. Built across packet **121** (`121-deep-agent-improvement-benchmark-mode`).\n55: - **Three pluggable seams** shared by all lanes: candidate-source, dispatcher, scorer. Entry: `scripts/shared/loop-host.cjs --mode=<lane>`. References/assets/scripts are organized by lane (`agent-improvement/`, `model-benchmark/`, `shared/`).\n56: - Shared runtime via the `deep-loop-runtime` peer skill (executor config, prompt-pack, validation, atomic state, coverage-graph, Bayesian scoring, fallback routing).\n57: \n58: Lane C is the natural third lane: same loop shape, same three seams, a new fixture/dispatcher/scorer triple scoped to *skills*.\n59: \n60: ---\n61: \n62: ## 3. Problem statement\n63: \n64: Skills are validated today in two ways, and both miss a critical failure class:\n65: \n66: - **`sk-doc` / `validate.sh`** check *document shape* (sections present, frontmatter valid, README/package conformance).\n67: - **Manual testing playbooks** (shipped inside many skills) check the *behavior the skill docs describe* — i.e. \"does the workflow do what the doc says when followed.\"\n68: \n69: Neither answers the question that actually determines a skill's real-world value:\n70: \n71: > When an AI is dropped into a realistic situation that *should* trigger this skill, does it (a) get routed to the skill at the right moment, (b) find and load the *correct, useful* references/assets **without being told which file to open**, and (c) reach a good outcome efficiently — or does the skill's structure/routing create bottlenecks that make AIs miss it, mis-route, over-load context, or fail to find the asset they needed?\n72: \n73: This is a **structure / routing / efficiency / usefulness** benchmark of the skill *as it is actually consumed*, not of the logic it describes. It is distinct from manual playbooks and from doc-shape validation. Its output must be **diagnostic and remediable** — ranked bottlenecks with concrete recommendations.\n74: \n75: ---\n76: \n77: ## 4. Goals\n78: \n79: - **G1.** Rename `deep-agent-improvement` → `deep-improvement` across every surface (skill dir, `SKILL.md`, commands, agent + runtime mirrors, skill-advisor graph, `descriptions.json`, and all cross-references) with zero dangling references and a green skill-advisor rebuild.\n80: - **G2.** Define Lane C (\"skill-benchmark\") precisely: what it measures, the fixture (scenario) schema, the unprompted-dispatch capture method, the scoring dimensions, and the remediation-report format.\n81: - **G3.** Implement Lane C as a third lane reusing the candidate/dispatcher/scorer seams and `loop-host.cjs --mode=skill-benchmark`, with a `/deep:start-skill-benchmark-loop` command.\n82: - **G4.** Produce a **Skill Benchmark Report** that ranks bottlenecks and gives actionable remediation a follow-up packet can act on.\n83: - **G5.** Keep Lane A and Lane B byte-identical when no `--mode=skill-benchmark` flag is set (no regression to existing lanes).\n84: - **G6.** Update all docs (two-lane → three-lane), README, advisor metadata, and run the standard hardening/deep-review gate.\n85: \n86: ### Non-Goals\n87: \n88: - **NG1.** Actually *remediating* the skills that Lane C flags (Lane C is diagnostic; remediation is separate, optionally via Lane A).\n89: - **NG2.** Replacing `sk-doc` doc-shape validation or the existing manual testing playbooks — Lane C is complementary, not a replacement.\n90: - **NG3.** Re-architecting the shared `deep-loop-runtime` (consume it; do not redesign it).\n91: - **NG4.** Renaming the per-lane command verbs unnecessarily (e.g. `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop` stays — it still improves *agents*); only the **skill name** must change. Command/agent naming decisions are recorded explicitly in Phase 002.\n92: \n93: ---\n94: \n95: ## 5. Scope\n96: \n97: **In scope:** the `deep-improvement` skill (post-rename), its commands/agent/mirrors, advisor metadata, and the new Lane C surface (references/assets/scripts under a `skill-benchmark/` domain), plus the deep-research that informs the design.\n98: \n99: **Out of scope:** changes to skills *other than* as benchmark *targets* of Lane C; changes to `deep-loop-runtime` internals; changes to `deep-review`/`deep-research` workflows beyond consuming them.\n100: \n101: **Frozen scope note:** per the Four Laws, scope defined here is frozen for the implementation phases. New ideas surfaced by research are recorded as follow-ups, not silently absorbed.\n102: \n103: ---\n104: \n105: ## 6. Sub-phase control\n106: \n107: This packet decomposes into the following ordered phases. Each child owns its own canonical docs.\n108: \n109: | Phase | Folder | Purpose | Depends on |\n110: | ----- | ------ | ------- | ---------- |\n111: | **001** | `001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/` | 20-iteration deep-research loop investigating Lane C design (what to measure, how to capture unprompted routing/discovery, scoring, remediation) **and** the rename impact map. Multi-model: 5× MiniMax-2.7, 5× DeepSeek-v4-pro, 5× GPT-5.5 (xhigh, fast), 5× Opus-4.8 native. | — |\n112: | **002** | `002-skill-rename-deep-improvement/` | Rename `deep-agent-improvement` → `deep-improvement` across all surfaces; advisor rebuild; no dangling refs. | 001 (impact map) |\n113: | **003** | `003-skill-benchmark-mode/` | Design + build Lane C in the renamed skill: scenario fixtures, unprompted dispatcher, routing/discovery/efficiency/usefulness scorer, report, `/deep:start-skill-benchmark-loop`. | 001, 002 |\n114: | **004** | `004-validation-and-docs/` | Three-lane doc updates, README, advisor metadata, hardening/deep-review gate, end-to-end validation. | 002, 003 |\n115: \n116: Resume policy: on a phase parent, follow `graph-metadata.json.derived.last_active_child_id`; if absent/stale, list children with statuses and pick.\n117: \n118: ---\n119: \n120: ## 7. Lane C — requirements (to be confirmed/refined by Phase 001 research)\n121: \n122: Working hypothesis for what Lane C measures. Phase 001 deep research validates, corrects, and operationalizes these; Phase 003 implements the converged design.\n123: \n124: - **R1 — Routing/activation accuracy.** Given a realistic prompt that *should* activate the target skill at a specific intent, does the skill-advisor + the skill's smart router select the right skill and the right intent/resource set? Measure precision/recall over a scenario suite (including near-miss negatives that should *not* activate).\n125: - **R2 — Unprompted reference/asset discovery.** For scenarios whose correct handling *requires* a specific reference/asset, does the agent autonomously load the right file via the router **without** being told the path? Measure discovery precision/recall and the count of irrelevant loads.\n126: - **R3 — Efficiency / bottlenecks.** Tool-calls and token cost to reach the needed resource; over-loading (too much context), under-loading (missing needed refs), ambiguous routing keys, fallback misfires, dead-ends.\n127: - **R4 — Usefulness (ablation).** Does the skill materially improve the scenario outcome vs a skill-off baseline? (skill-on vs skill-off delta.)\n128: - **R5 — Structural connectivity.** Orphan references/assets (present but never routable), router keys that never fire for any real scenario, missing triggers for real scenario classes, broken/over-broad routing.\n129: - **R6 — Actionable output.** A ranked **Skill Benchmark Report**: per-dimension scores + ranked bottlenecks + concrete remediations (add trigger X, intent Y never fires for class Z, reference A orphaned, scenario class B needs asset C surfaced).\n130: \n131: ### Architecture fit (working hypothesis)\n132: \n133: - **Fixtures** = a scenario set per target skill: realistic prompt + expected activation + expected resource(s) + correct-outcome rubric, including negatives.\n134: - **Dispatcher** = run each scenario against an executor in a *hint-free* harness, capturing the resource-load trace and tool trace (what it opened, in what order, how many calls).\n135: - **Scorer** = compare actual vs expected across R1–R5 → skill-benchmark dimensions; emit R6 report. Reuses the deterministic-checks + pluggable-grader shape of the Lane B 5-dim scorer.\n136: - **Mode** = `loop-host.cjs --mode=skill-benchmark`; every state record carries `mode: skill-benchmark`; reports carry a `scoringMethod`.\n137: - **Promotion** = Lane C is **advisory/diagnostic** by default (emits a report; does not mutate the target skill). Optional hand-off: feed findings into Lane A to actually improve a `SKILL.md`.\n138: \n139: ---\n140: \n141: ## 8. Success criteria\n142: \n143: - **SC1.** Phase 001 deep-research loop completes (convergence or max iterations) with all state files consistent, `research/research.md` synthesized, and the multi-model split executed (5/5/5/5 across MiniMax-2.7 / DeepSeek-v4-pro / GPT-5.5-xhigh-fast / Opus-4.8-native).\n144: - **SC2.** Rename (Phase 002) leaves zero dangling `deep-agent-improvement` references where `deep-improvement` is intended; skill-advisor rebuild + validate are green; Lane A/B commands still run.\n145: - **SC3.** Lane C (Phase 003) runs end-to-end on at least one real target skill and emits a Skill Benchmark Report with ranked, actionable bottlenecks; Lane A/B behavior is unchanged when the mode flag is absent.\n146: - **SC4.** Docs/README/advisor reflect three lanes; hardening/deep-review gate passes (Phase 004).\n147: - **SC5.** `validate.sh <packet> --strict` is green at parent and per active child.\n148: \n149: ---\n150: \n151: ## 9. Risks\n152: \n153: - **Rename blast radius.** `deep-agent-improvement` is referenced by commands, the agent + 3 runtime mirrors, the advisor graph, `descriptions.json`, the sentinel `sk-prompt-small-model`, and root docs. Mitigation: Phase 001 produces an exhaustive impact map before Phase 002 touches anything.\n154: - **Lane C measurement validity.** \"Did the AI find the right asset unprompted\" must be measured without leaking the answer into the prompt. Mitigation: hint-free dispatch harness + held-out expected-resource keys; this is a primary research question.\n155: - **Non-determinism.** AI routing varies run-to-run. Mitigation: repeatability runs + report variance, mirroring Lane B's stability evidence.\n156: - **Scope creep into remediation.** Easy to drift from \"diagnose\" to \"fix\". Mitigation: NG1 freezes Lane C as diagnostic.\n157: \n158: ---\n159: \n160: ## 10. References\n161: \n162: - Skill under change: `.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md` (→ `deep-improvement`).\n163: - Sibling packet (Lane B, template): `.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/121-deep-agent-improvement-benchmark-mode/`.\n164: - Deep-research contract: `.opencode/skills/deep-research/SKILL.md`; command `.opencode/commands/deep/start-research-loop.md`.\n165: - Shared runtime: `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/SKILL.md`.\n166: - Doc/validation: `.opencode/skills/sk-doc/`, `system-spec-kit` validate.\n167: \n168: ---\n169: \n170: ## 11. Open questions (for Phase 001 research)\n171: \n172: - OQ1. Exact scoring dimensions + weights for Lane C (R1–R5) and how to normalize across skills of different shapes.\n173: - OQ2. How to build a credible *hint-free* dispatch harness that still captures the resource-load trace.\n174: - OQ3. Whether activation accuracy should be measured against the skill-advisor, the in-`SKILL.md` smart router, or both as separate sub-scores.\n175: - OQ4. Scenario authoring: hand-authored vs generated-from-the-skill's-own-triggers (and how to avoid circularity).\n176: - OQ5. The exact rename surface list + safe ordering (advisor graph + mirrors + descriptions).\n177: - OQ6. Whether `/deep:start-skill-benchmark-loop` should reuse the model-benchmark command scaffold or get its own.\n\n(End of file - total 177 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: \"Feature Specification: deep-improvement — skill-benchmark mode + rename\"\ndescription: \"Phase parent: rename deep-agent-improvement to deep-improvement and add Lane C (skill-benchmark) measuring a skill's real-world routing, unprompted reference/asset discovery, efficiency, and usefulness; multi-model deep research (001) informs rename (002), Lane C build (003), and validation/docs (004).\"\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode\"\n  - \"skill-benchmark mode\"\n  - \"deep-improvement skill rename\"\nimportance_tier: \"important\"\ncontextType: \"implementation\"\n_memory:\n  continuity:\n    packet_pointer: \"skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode\"\n    last_updated_at: \"2026-05-30T00:00:00Z\"\n    last_updated_by: \"claude-opus\"\n    recent_action: \"Authored parent spec + 4-phase structure\"\n    next_safe_action: \"Run multi-model deep research in 001-skill-benchmark-deep-research\"\n    blockers: []\n    completion_pct: 10\n    open_questions: []\n    answered_questions: []","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/spec.md","time":{"start":1780128174579,"end":1780128174584}},"id":"prt_e77e8519a001tzM32WLJC6t0Zb","sessionID":"ses_18818249cffeInllmWUcVkPFl1","messageID":"msg_e77e8390f001cmfTlwe5oWz4bn"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780128175059,"sessionID":"ses_18818249cffeInllmWUcVkPFl1","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"webfetch","callID":"call_function_uq6cuwlcg0ve_2","state":{"status":"error","input":{"url":"https://platform.ai.com/blog/introducing-gpt-bootcamp-ai-evaluation-harness"},"error":"Transport error (GET https://platform.ai.com/blog/introducing-gpt-bootcamp-ai-evaluation-harness)","time":{"start":1780128174740,"end":1780128175059}},"id":"prt_e77e851f5001XQnd6axWZFHb8b","sessionID":"ses_18818249cffeInllmWUcVkPFl1","messageID":"msg_e77e8390f001cmfTlwe5oWz4bn"}}
