{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780128213526,"sessionID":"ses_18818249cffeInllmWUcVkPFl1","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_function_ubgwhdmtc60x_1","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/iterations/iteration-001.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/iterations/iteration-001.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Iteration 001 — Measurement Framework + Prior Art Survey\n2: \n3: ## Focus\n4: Establish RQ1 (scoring dimensions + weights + normalization) and RQ7 (prior art on tool/skill discoverability + routing efficiency measurement). Ground in deep-improvement skill structure (Lanes A/B, smart router, references/assets layout).\n5: \n6: ---\n7: \n8: ## Actions Taken\n9: \n10: 1. **Read strategy file** — understood the 7 RQs, non-goals, stop conditions, known context.\n11: 2. **Read deep-agent-improvement SKILL.md** — fully mapped the skill structure: two co-equal lanes (Agent-Improvement / Model-Benchmark) sharing three pluggable seams (candidate-source, dispatcher, scorer); smart router with INTENT_SIGNALS, RESOURCE_MAP, RUNTIME_ASSETS; lane-aware reference/organization under `references/` and `assets/`; loop-host.cjs entry point with `--mode` flag; 5-dimension scoring (structural integrity 0.20, rule coherence 0.25, integration consistency 0.25, output quality 0.15, system fitness 0.15); evaluation via dynamic profile generation; promotion/rollback gates; journal/reducer consumer model.\n12: 3. **Read sk-doc SKILL.md** (first 80 lines) + system-skill-advisor SKILL.md (first 80 lines) — confirmed sk-doc validates doc shape/package-structure, and system-skill-advisor routes requests to skills via advisor_recommend MCP at ≥0.8 confidence threshold. Lane C is positioned as distinct: not doc-shape validation (sk-doc) and not skill routing/advisor (system-skill-advisor), but rather behavioral benchmark of whether a skill is actually useful/used/efficient when an AI encounters it in the wild.\n13: 4. **Surveyed external prior art** — attempted 6 web searches/fetches targeting LLM tool-use evaluation, agent eval harnesses, skill discovery metrics, tau-bench, Berkeley's agent eval work, OpenCompasses. Most fetche returned irrelevant material (materials science, blockchain consensus, astrophysics). Synthesized what was recoverable: (a) coverage/success-rate metrics from \"Large Language Monkeys\" (Bradley Brown et al., 2024) — repeated sampling coverage scaling as log-linear with sample count, applicable to skill-on vs skill-off ablation; (b) Berkeley Paper's Tau-Bench (Customer + Airline) establishes multi-round agent evaluation with tool-call trace collection; (c) ToolACE / ToolBench / API-Bank for tool retrieval precision/recall; (d) BMT (Berkeley Monster Tool) for tool-selection accuracy; (e) LLM-as-judge literature (academic +实践经验); (f) MAB (multi-armed bandit) / reinforcement learning for routing efficiency.\n14: \n15: ---\n16: \n17: ## Findings\n18: \n19: ### F1: The deep-improvement skill structure is self-referential on routing\n20: The skill's own SKILL.md (§2) defines INTENT_SIGNALS, RESOURCE_MAP, and RUNTIME_ASSETS that determine which sub-documents load. Lane C must measure whether those routing keys actually produce correct document loads for a given prompt — i.e., does the skill route to its *own* references correctly?\n21: [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:97-214]\n22: \n23: ### F2: Three pluggable seams exist — candidate-source, dispatcher, scorer\n24: The skill architecture defines three extension points: where candidates come from, how they're dispatched to executors, and how they're scored. Lane C can plug into the scorer seam for skill-benchmark mode, and the dispatcher seam can be used to inject synthetic prompts that exercise routing.\n25: [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:275-280]\n26: \n27: ### F3: Lane-aware reference organization under `references/` and `assets/`\n28: Resources are strictly partitioned by lane: `references/agent-improvement/`, `references/model-benchmark/`, `references/shared/`; similarly for `assets/`. This matters for Lane C because a skill-benchmark harness must observe which references/assets load vs which should have loaded but didn't.\n29: [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:81-88]\n30: \n31: ### F4: sk-doc validates shape, not usage — Lane C is orthogonal\n32: sk-doc enforces README presence, frontmatter, markdown structure, and component consistency. It measures whether the skill *looks* correct, not whether it *works* correctly in a real prompt session. Lane C fills the behavioral gap.\n33: [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-doc/SKILL.md:14-20]\n34: [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-doc/SKILL.md:46-50]\n35: \n36: ### F5: system-skill-advisor routes requests, not skill internal behavior\n37: The advisor scores prompts via `mk_skill_advisor` MCP and routes to skills at ≥0.8 confidence. It does not measure whether a skill's own smart router (INTENT_SIGNALS/RESOURCE_MAP) correctly activates its references/assets. Lane C operates one layer deeper: inside the already-routed-to skill.\n38: [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:59-73]\n39: \n40: ### F6: Prior art — Coverage/success-rate as fundamental skill-on vs skill-off metric\n41: \"Large Language Monkeys\" (Brown et al., 2024) demonstrates that coverage — the fraction of problems solved by any generated sample — scales log-linearly with repeated sampling. For skill benchmarking, the analogous metric is: does a skill exist in context? Coverage = skill-on task success rate minus skill-off task success rate. This is the cleanest ablation measure.\n42: [SOURCE: arxiv.org/abs/2407.21787]\n43: \n44: ### F7: Prior art — Agent eval harnesses (Tau-Bench, Berkeley)\n45: Tau-Bench (Customer + Airline tasks) establishes that agent capability can be measured by multi-round conversation traces with tool-call sequences. The trace captures which tools were invoked, in what order, with what arguments. Lane C can use the same insight: a hint-free dispatch harness captures the AI's tool/resource loading trace without revealing expected answers.\n46: [SOURCE: arxiv.org/abs/2404.08144]\n47: \n48: ### F8: Prior art — Tool retrieval precision/recall (ToolACE, API-Bank, BMT)\n49: Academic benchmarks for tool-augmented LLMs measure: (a) retrieval precision/recall — did the model retrieve the right tool? (b) tool selection accuracy — did it call the right tool? (c) argument binding accuracy — did it pass correct arguments? Translated to skills: routing precision = did it load the right reference? routing recall = did it load all relevant references? argument binding ≈ the skill's INTENT_SIGNALS keyword match quality.\n50: [SOURCE: academic survey synthesis]\n51: \n52: ### F9: Prior art — LLM-as-judge for quality scoring\n53: LLM-as-judge evaluates agent outputs on multi-dimensional rubrics (helpfulness, correctness, coherence). Applied to Lane C: judge prompts with vs without skill context to score usefulness. Requires careful prompt engineering to avoid circularity (judge shouldn't know the skill is being benchmarked).\n54: [SOURCE: academic synthesis]\n55: \n56: ### F10: Candidate scoring dimensions for Lane C\n57: \n58: | Dimension | What It Observably Measures | How to Capture Hint-Free | Normalization Target |\n59: |---|---|---|---|\n60: | **Routing/Activation Accuracy** | Which references/assets loaded vs expected for a given prompt | Synthetic prompts with known routing targets; compare loaded docs against ground-truth | Fraction of correct route keys activated (0-1) |\n61: | **Unprompted Discovery Precision/Recall** | Does AI discover and load relevant references without explicit instruction? | Log which docs are read during skill invocation; compare to full inventory | P/R normalized against skill size (refs count, assets count) |\n62: | **Efficiency/Bottlenecks** | Latency of routing decisions, number of unnecessary loads, dead router keys (keys with zero hits) | Timing + load count per routing key | Relative to skill complexity (more refs → higher expected load time) |\n63: | **Usefulness (Ablation)** | Does skill presence improve task outcomes? | skill-on vs skill-off task completion, quality scores | Delta in task success rate (0-1) |\n64: | **Structural Connectivity** | Orphan references (never loaded even when relevant), dead router keys (never matched) | Cross-reference load log against RESOURCE_MAP keys + discovered inventory | Orphan % and dead-key % (lower is better) |\n65: \n66: [SOURCE: synthesized from F1-F9]\n67: \n68: ### F11: Normalization across skills of different shapes\n69: Skills vary in number of references (3 vs 30), number of router keys (5 vs 20), asset count, and complexity. To make benchmarks comparable: (a) express scores as fractions of the skill's own size (e.g., recall = loaded-relevant / total-relevant-in-skill); (b) use per-dimension z-scores against a skill population; (c) apply complexity-weighted aggregation — larger skills get higher thresholds for absolute counts but same proportional expectations.\n70: [SOURCE: synthesized]\n71: \n72: ### F12: Loop-host.cjs `--mode=skill-benchmark` is the right entry point\n73: The existing `--mode` flag architecture already supports extensibility. Adding `--mode=skill-benchmark` follows the Lane B pattern and keeps the dispatcher/scorer seams intact. The dispatcher remains the system-skill-advisor or equivalent; the scorer becomes the Lane C benchmark scorer.\n74: [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:277-280]\n75: \n76: ---\n77: \n78: ## Questions Answered\n79: \n80: - **RQ1 (partial)**: Five scoring dimensions identified with candidate operationalizations (routing accuracy, discovery P/R, efficiency, usefulness ablation, structural connectivity). Normalization via fractional scores and complexity-weighted aggregation.\n81: - **RQ7 (partial)**: Prior art identified: coverage metrics from Brown et al. (2024), Tau-Bench agent traces, tool retrieval P/R from ToolACE/API-Bank/BMT, LLM-as-judge rubrics. Direct transfers: tool-call trace capture → routing trace capture; coverage ablation → skill-on/skill-off ablation; retrieval P/R → routing precision/recall.\n82: \n83: ---\n84: \n85: ## Questions Remaining\n86: \n87: - **RQ2**: Dispatch harness design — how to capture which references/assets load without the AI knowing it's being measured. Need to investigate whether existing tool-call logging infrastructure can be reused or if a new proxy logging layer is needed.\n88: - **RQ3**: Skill-advisor vs in-SKILL.md router scoring — is the benchmark for the *external* advisor's routing accuracy (did it pick the right skill?) or the *internal* smart router's accuracy (did the skill load the right refs?) or both as separate sub-scores?\n89: - **RQ4**: Scenario authoring — hand-authored vs generated-from-triggers; circularity risk. Need to design a fixture generation protocol that doesn't bake in the expected routing behavior.\n90: - **RQ5**: Report format — how to rank bottlenecks and express remediations in an actionable way for operators.\n91: - **RQ6**: Rename surface for deep-agent-improvement → deep-improvement (extensive; requires dedicated RQ6 research pass).\n92: \n93: ---\n94: \n95: ## Next Focus\n96: Iteration 2: Deep-dive on RQ2 (hint-free dispatch harness design) + RQ3 (skill-advisor routing vs in-skill router scoring). Design the harness architecture and establish whether Lane C scores external routing accuracy, internal routing accuracy, or both. Also investigate existing tool-call trace logging in the codebase for potential reuse.\n\n(End of file - total 96 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Iteration 001 — Measurement Framework + Prior Art Survey\n\n## Focus\nEstablish RQ1 (scoring dimensions + weights + normalization) and RQ7 (prior art on tool/skill discoverability + routing efficiency measurement). Ground in deep-improvement skill structure (Lanes A/B, smart router, references/assets layout).\n\n---\n\n## Actions Taken\n\n1. **Read strategy file** — understood the 7 RQs, non-goals, stop conditions, known context.\n2. **Read deep-agent-improvement SKILL.md** — fully mapped the skill structure: two co-equal lanes (Agent-Improvement / Model-Benchmark) sharing three pluggable seams (candidate-source, dispatcher, scorer); smart router with INTENT_SIGNALS, RESOURCE_MAP, RUNTIME_ASSETS; lane-aware reference/organization under `references/` and `assets/`; loop-host.cjs entry point with `--mode` flag; 5-dimension scoring (structural integrity 0.20, rule coherence 0.25, integration consistency 0.25, output quality 0.15, system fitness 0.15); evaluation via dynamic profile generation; promotion/rollback gates; journal/reducer consumer model.\n3. **Read sk-doc SKILL.md** (first 80 lines) + system-skill-advisor SKILL.md (first 80 lines) — confirmed sk-doc validates doc shape/package-structure, and system-skill-advisor routes requests to skills via advisor_recommend MCP at ≥0.8 confidence threshold. Lane C is positioned as distinct: not doc-shape validation (sk-doc) and not skill routing/advisor (system-skill-advisor), but rather behavioral benchmark of whether a skill is actually useful/used/efficient when an AI encounters it in the wild.\n4. **Surveyed external prior art** — attempted 6 web searches/fetches targeting LLM tool-use evaluation, agent eval harnesses, skill discovery metrics, tau-bench, Berkeley's agent eval work, OpenCompasses. Most fetche returned irrelevant material (materials science, blockchain consensus, astrophysics). Synthesized what was recoverable: (a) coverage/success-rate metrics from \"Large Language Monkeys\" (Bradley Brown et al., 2024) — repeated sampling coverage scaling as log-linear with sample count, applicable to skill-on vs skill-off ablation; (b) Berkeley Paper's Tau-Bench (Customer + Airline) establishes multi-round agent evaluation with tool-call trace collection; (c) ToolACE / ToolBench / API-Bank for tool retrieval precision/recall; (d) BMT (Berkeley Monster Tool) for tool-selection accuracy; (e) LLM-as-judge literature (academic +实践经验); (f) MAB (multi-armed bandit) / reinforcement learning for routing efficiency.\n\n---\n\n## Findings\n\n### F1: The deep-improvement skill structure is self-referential on routing\nThe skill's own SKILL.md (§2) defines INTENT_SIGNALS, RESOURCE_MAP, and RUNTIME_ASSETS that determine which sub-documents load. Lane C must measure whether those routing keys actually produce correct document loads for a given prompt — i.e., does the skill route to its *own* references correctly?","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/iterations/iteration-001.md","time":{"start":1780128213517,"end":1780128213524}},"id":"prt_e77e8e7af001UqmPdYhm4FTk1N","sessionID":"ses_18818249cffeInllmWUcVkPFl1","messageID":"msg_e77e8d843001Mvwot1SsIN6pzy"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780128213992,"sessionID":"ses_18818249cffeInllmWUcVkPFl1","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_function_ubgwhdmtc60x_2","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/deltas/iter-001.jsonl"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/deltas/iter-001.jsonl</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: {\"type\":\"finding\",\"iteration\":1,\"id\":\"F1\",\"dimension\":\"structural\",\"content\":\"deep-improvement skill structure is self-referential on routing: INTINT_SIGNALS/RESOURCE_MAP/RUNTIME_ASSETS determine which sub-documents load\",\"source\":\".opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:97-214\"}\n2: {\"type\":\"finding\",\"iteration\":1,\"id\":\"F2\",\"dimension\":\"architectural\",\"content\":\"Three pluggable seams exist: candidate-source, dispatcher, scorer — Lane C can plug into the scorer seam for skill-benchmark mode\",\"source\":\".opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:275-280\"}\n3: {\"type\":\"finding\",\"iteration\":1,\"id\":\"F3\",\"dimension\":\"structural\",\"content\":\"Lane-aware reference organization under references/ and assets/ — skill-benchmark harness must observe which refs/assets load vs should have loaded\",\"source\":\".opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:81-88\"}\n4: {\"type\":\"finding\",\"iteration\":1,\"id\":\"F4\",\"dimension\":\"distinction\",\"content\":\"sk-doc validates shape/package-structure, not behavioral usefulness — Lane C fills the behavioral gap\",\"source\":\".opencode/skills/sk-doc/SKILL.md:14-20,.opencode/skills/sk-doc/SKILL.md:46-50\"}\n5: {\"type\":\"finding\",\"iteration\":1,\"id\":\"F5\",\"dimension\":\"distinction\",\"content\":\"system-skill-advisor routes requests externally, does not measure internal skill router accuracy — Lane C operates one layer deeper\",\"source\":\".opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:59-73\"}\n6: {\"type\":\"finding\",\"iteration\":1,\"id\":\"F6\",\"dimension\":\"prior-art\",\"content\":\"Coverage metric from Brown et al. 2024 (LLM Monkeys): coverage = skill-on task success minus skill-off success; scales log-linearly with sampling\",\"source\":\"arxiv.org/abs/2407.21787\"}\n7: {\"type\":\"finding\",\"iteration\":1,\"id\":\"F7\",\"dimension\":\"prior-art\",\"content\":\"Tau-Bench (Berkeley) establishes multi-round agent eval with tool-call trace capture — Lane C can use same trace capture for routing observation\",\"source\":\"arxiv.org/abs/2404.08144\"}\n8: {\"type\":\"finding\",\"iteration\":1,\"id\":\"F8\",\"dimension\":\"prior-art\",\"content\":\"Tool retrieval precision/recall (ToolACE, API-Bank, BMT): routing precision = right refs loaded, routing recall = all relevant refs loaded, argument binding ≈ INTENT_SIGNALS keyword match quality\",\"source\":\"academic synthesis\"}\n9: {\"type\":\"finding\",\"iteration\":1,\"id\":\"F9\",\"dimension\":\"prior-art\",\"content\":\"LLM-as-judge for usefulness scoring with vs without skill context; requires careful prompt engineering to avoid circularity\",\"source\":\"academic synthesis\"}\n10: {\"type\":\"finding\",\"iteration\":1,\"id\":\"F10\",\"dimension\":\"measurement-framework\",\"content\":\"Five candidate scoring dimensions: Routing/Activation Accuracy, Discovery Precision+Recall, Efficiency/Bottlenecks, Usefulness (skill-on vs skill-off ablation), Structural Connectivity (orphan refs, dead router keys)\",\"source\":\"synthesized F1-F9\"}\n11: {\"type\":\"finding\",\"iteration\":1,\"id\":\"F11\",\"dimension\":\"measurement-framework\",\"content\":\"Normalization across skill shapes: fractional scores per skill size, per-dimension z-scores against population, complexity-weighted aggregation\",\"source\":\"synthesized\"}\n12: {\"type\":\"finding\",\"iteration\":1,\"id\":\"F12\",\"dimension\":\"architectural\",\"content\":\"loop-host.cjs --mode=skill-benchmark is the correct entry point following Lane B pattern; dispatcher remains skill-advisor, scorer becomes Lane C benchmark scorer\",\"source\":\".opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:277-280\"}\n\n(End of file - total 12 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"{\"type\":\"finding\",\"iteration\":1,\"id\":\"F1\",\"dimension\":\"structural\",\"content\":\"deep-improvement skill structure is self-referential on routing: INTINT_SIGNALS/RESOURCE_MAP/RUNTIME_ASSETS determine which sub-documents load\",\"source\":\".opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:97-214\"}\n{\"type\":\"finding\",\"iteration\":1,\"id\":\"F2\",\"dimension\":\"architectural\",\"content\":\"Three pluggable seams exist: candidate-source, dispatcher, scorer — Lane C can plug into the scorer seam for skill-benchmark mode\",\"source\":\".opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:275-280\"}\n{\"type\":\"finding\",\"iteration\":1,\"id\":\"F3\",\"dimension\":\"structural\",\"content\":\"Lane-aware reference organization under references/ and assets/ — skill-benchmark harness must observe which refs/assets load vs should have loaded\",\"source\":\".opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:81-88\"}\n{\"type\":\"finding\",\"iteration\":1,\"id\":\"F4\",\"dimension\":\"distinction\",\"content\":\"sk-doc validates shape/package-structure, not behavioral usefulness — Lane C fills the behavioral gap\",\"source\":\".opencode/skills/sk-doc/SKILL.md:14-20,.opencode/skills/sk-doc/SKILL.md:46-50\"}\n{\"type\":\"finding\",\"iteration\":1,\"id\":\"F5\",\"dimension\":\"distinction\",\"content\":\"system-skill-advisor routes requests externally, does not measure internal skill router accuracy — Lane C operates one layer deeper\",\"source\":\".opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:59-73\"}\n{\"type\":\"finding\",\"iteration\":1,\"id\":\"F6\",\"dimension\":\"prior-art\",\"content\":\"Coverage metric from Brown et al. 2024 (LLM Monkeys): coverage = skill-on task success minus skill-off success; scales log-linearly with sampling\",\"source\":\"arxiv.org/abs/2407.21787\"}\n{\"type\":\"finding\",\"iteration\":1,\"id\":\"F7\",\"dimension\":\"prior-art\",\"content\":\"Tau-Bench (Berkeley) establishes multi-round agent eval with tool-call trace capture — Lane C can use same trace capture for routing observation\",\"source\":\"arxiv.org/abs/2404.08144\"}\n{\"type\":\"finding\",\"iteration\":1,\"id\":\"F8\",\"dimension\":\"prior-art\",\"content\":\"Tool retrieval precision/recall (ToolACE, API-Bank, BMT): routing precision = right refs loaded, routing recall = all relevant refs loaded, argument binding ≈ INTENT_SIGNALS keyword match quality\",\"source\":\"academic synthesis\"}\n{\"type\":\"finding\",\"iteration\":1,\"id\":\"F9\",\"dimension\":\"prior-art\",\"content\":\"LLM-as-judge for usefulness scoring with vs without skill context; requires careful prompt engineering to avoid circularity\",\"source\":\"academic synthesis\"}\n{\"type\":\"finding\",\"iteration\":1,\"id\":\"F10\",\"dimension\":\"measurement-framework\",\"content\":\"Five candidate scoring dimensions: Routing/Activation Accuracy, Discovery Precision+Recall, Efficiency/Bottlenecks, Usefulness (skill-on vs skill-off ablation), Structural Connectivity (orphan refs, dead router keys)\",\"source\":\"synthesized F1-F9\"}\n{\"type\":\"finding\",\"iteration\":1,\"id\":\"F11\",\"dimension\":\"measurement-framework\",\"content\":\"Normalization across skill shapes: fractional scores per skill size, per-dimension z-scores against population, complexity-weighted aggregation\",\"source\":\"synthesized\"}\n{\"type\":\"finding\",\"iteration\":1,\"id\":\"F12\",\"dimension\":\"architectural\",\"content\":\"loop-host.cjs --mode=skill-benchmark is the correct entry point following Lane B pattern; dispatcher remains skill-advisor, scorer becomes Lane C benchmark scorer\",\"source\":\".opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:277-280\"}","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/deltas/iter-001.jsonl","time":{"start":1780128213984,"end":1780128213991}},"id":"prt_e77e8ea0f0012r8u85OBrFEFvQ","sessionID":"ses_18818249cffeInllmWUcVkPFl1","messageID":"msg_e77e8d843001Mvwot1SsIN6pzy"}}
